    <div class="AssessmentProblem.identifier">102669</div>
    <div class="AssessmentProblem.type">ShortAnswerResponse</div>
    <div class="AssessmentProblem.statement"><p>This diagram&#xA0;shows a large&#xA0;rectangle and a small rectangle.&#xA0;The ratio of the length to the width of the small&#xA0;rectangle is <span class="math math-repaired" data-png-file-id="13427">\(3:2\)</span>.</p>

<p><img class="h-max-height--16-lines" src="/image_files/29473.png" /></p>

<ol>
	<li>What is the ratio of the length to the width of the large&#xA0;rectangle?</li>
	<li>Draw a different rectangle whose ratio of length to width is equivalent to these two. Now draw one more rectangle.</li>
	<li>Check that the ratios of length to width for all four rectangles are equivalent. Explain how you know that the ratios are all equivalent.</li>
</ol>
</div>
    <div class="AssessmentProblem.solution"><ol>
	<li>
<span class="math math-repaired" data-png-file-id="8149">\(6:4\)</span>.</li>
	<li>Answers vary. Sample response:
	<p><img class="h-max-height--15-lines" src="/image_files/30678.png" /></p>
	</li>
	<li>The ratios of length to width of the four&#xA0;rectangles are <span class="math math-repaired" data-png-file-id="13427">\(3:2\)</span>, <span class="math math-repaired" data-png-file-id="8149">\(6:4\)</span>, <span class="math math-repaired" data-png-file-id="8477">\(9:6\)</span>, and <span class="math math-repaired" data-png-file-id="38602">\(12:8\)</span>. These ratios are&#xA0;equivalent because in each ratio there are&#xA0;3 units of length for every&#xA0;2 units of width.</li>
</ol>
</div>
